@NYC Traveler

Wonderful news! I'm so glad you were there for the birth and got to be one of the first to hold little Maya in your arms.
I'm truly delighted for you!

@Francis

The opening song of that musical always makes my spirits soar!

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O5APc0z49wg" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O5APc0z49wg</a>

@Beth 

The Guardian ran a feature on oleato a few years ago. Apparently it is loved by some and loathed by others. Must be a matter of taste. I've never tried it myself, but who knows, maybe it works? Apparently the fats from the olive oil make the taste more intense yet the texture more silky.

In Polish "fiskus" is a collective noun used to describe the fiscal authorities - it rolls of the tongue better than "organy podatkowe" (tax authorities) or "administracja celno-skarbowa" (tax and duties administration) 🤣. Your IRS would be described as fiskus in my language.

@Lee 

You made me smile 😀

Thanks!

@Jim 

To be fair, that would be the only sign of the ones mentioned here that would make the whole thing art. It gets my vote!

See you at the MoMA, wet pants bench!

@David Connell 

I last visited Toruń in 1994 and already then it's wasn't half bad.

I just have to defend my city. Warsaw never was soulless. It definitely isn't now. When were you here last? The changes since joining the EU in 2004, and especially under the latest mayor (who will likey become Poland's new president in a few months) transformed the city, especially its historic areas and the riverbanks.

@Andrzej 

I'm glad you saw my comment and thanks so much for the reply! I'm told some of my ancestors came from Poland, thence to Luxembourg, then the US, so another reason to visit. Thanks for the other tips. TBH, I was curious about your real view of Poland as a place to visit, since I believe you have mentioned a preference to travel elsewhere; but we all often take our own homelands for granted, being always accessible. 

@David Connell

Have a look at Rick Steves' program on Poland. The musical contribution of Poles is given its due, and it's a very interesting hour with an up-to-date view of the country. You'll see why Warsaw had appeal for me, even with the vestiges of communistic architecture. Apart from the interesting new buildings, parks and markets, they've added some color to the drab old blocks. And it was a hoot watching Rick get a tour of the city from a guide driving a soviet-era sedan. I believe Andrzej lives in a very cosmopolitan, desireable place.

@Mtmetz 

I wouldn't recommend visiting Poland over places like France, Italy or Spain. But if you do want to come, you will have plenty of things to see and do. We have historical monuments, peaceful countryside, forests, lakes, rivers, good food and lodging.

I rarely travel around Poland myself, but when I do, I'm often surprised by just how interesting thus country can be. A few years ago I went on a trip to Dolny Śląsk (Lower Silesia, the region south of Wrocław). We traveled across fields and forests on winding mountain roads, stayed in palatial hotels, visited castles (Bolków, Grodziec and others), enjoyed gems like the towns of Świdnica (home to a Gothic cathedral and an incredible, wooden, Baroque church) Jelenia Góra and Paczków. We had a great time.

@MB 
It's the state song. Every school kid in the state has to stand with their class and sing it, over and over, for years.

As a kid who just wanted to disappear and escape notice, being required to sing that thing, with its enforced Broadway show enthusiasm, wasn't fun. I still can't stand to hear it.

@Steve L
I did! I work on the principle that a three letter answer to any bat and ball game will be RBI. Unless it’s cricket, in which case it would be LBW (leg before wicket).

I try to retain the nuggets of wisdom you give us; they don’t always stay in there, but I try.

@Helen Wright
Is salt in coffee common over there? It's not in the US, though it seems to be a thing in Mexico.

One time at work, my brother-in-law sat down to drink his coffee, and one of his Mexican coworkers threw some salt into it. His reaction, of course, was "dude why?!" He ended up liking it, though.

@Helen Wright
@Mean Old Lady
@Kate

To answer you both; no, it’s not common. I began eating a keto diet a year ago, which morphed into semi-carnivore. I eat mostly animal products plus a few veg and berries. Part of this meant giving up milk (too high in lactose). I hate black coffee so added butter. Tastes fab. I need to add salt to my diet as I don’t eat processed foods, so added that too. It really does taste great. Kind of like adding salt to chocolate, that sweet/salt combo works well. 

Why keto? By dropping carbs I’ve reversed T2 diabetes, to my Dr.’s surprise. Won’t be going back to them anytime soon.

@Mean Old Lady 

You might try oatmilk... My review of it in coffee would work well with today's theme, haha. A few years ago, it was rather too watery for me, but more recently I had it at a cafe and it was pretty tasty! I was told to look for "barista" labeling on the carton. (So far, I'm still a cow's milk gal, because I still can...)

@Helen Wright

I remember butter coffee being all the rage maybe five or so years ago. Something about yak coffee maybe? But looking it up now, it seems Silicon Valley popularized it around that time. Perhaps I'll give it a go!

@Graphic
Yeah, I don’t use oil for anything anymore. It’s butter or dripping. Surprisingly I find them to have a more satisfying, less greasy mouth feel than even the good olive or avocado oils.

Do try the butter coffee; I use about a half teaspoon to a large mug, with a pinch of salt. It doesn’t taste of butter, just gives a very smooth mouth feel. I confess the salt took a little getting used to, so maybe just a tiny bit to start. Enjoy!

@Jim As another math geek,  I'm with you but also DOLDRUM (Sam has always been weak on sailing terms --and that even has other meanings.)
I'm willing to concede that ORMULO might be too niche.
So I'm still a few points low.

@RozzieGrandma 

Yes, I got that at the end. I still think it was a stretch.
Digestible, I suppose, but not tasty-mouthful. To use other four-syllable descriptors.

@Barry Ancona

Thanks for that link. 

